### Tested versions

v4.4.stable.arch_linux

### System information

Godot v4.4.stable unknown - Arch Linux #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu, 27 Feb 2025 18:09:44 +0000 on X11 - X11 display driver, Multi-window, 2 monitors - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated AMD Radeon RX 5700 XT (RADV NAVI10) - AMD Ryzen 9 5950X 16-Core Processor (32 threads)

### Issue description

If exporting a tool button with `@export_tool_button` (or equivalent using `_get_property_list` etc.) Pressing the button will not call the function on all of the selected nodes which are of same type, although the button is properly visible.

Setting normal exported properties works as normal.

The inspector plugin connects the button to the `_call_action` function which calls the callable in the node:

https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/f2cc3f12750adae431384d7bac2f75d1c7e506be/editor/plugins/tool_button_editor_plugin.cpp#L72

https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/f2cc3f12750adae431384d7bac2f75d1c7e506be/editor/plugins/tool_button_editor_plugin.cpp#L39-L53

Previously I have circumvented this on my custom tool buttons (created with `EditorInspectorPlugin` before `@editor_tool_button` was implemented), by connecting the button to a intermediary function in the inspector plugin, which then parses the selected nodes for correct node types:

```gdscript
func _parse_property(object, p_type, p_name, etc...):
    if object is TargetNodeExample:
        return add_btn(p_name)
    elif object.get_class() == "MultiNodeEdit":
        # MultiNodeEdit is not exposed to gdscript, thus this workaround
        # to find if the wanted nodes are selected
        # otherwise could get the node list from MultiNodeEdit directly
        for node in EditorInterface.get_selection().get_selected_nodes():
            if node is TargetNodeExample:
                return add_btn(p_name)

func add_btn(p_name)
    if p_name == "/btn_example":
        var btn = Button.new()
        btn.text = "example"
        if !btn.pressed.is_connected(btn_pressed):
            btn.pressed.connect(btn_pressed)
        return true # removes original control

func btn_pressed():
    # get the nodes again for safety, in case a node has somehow disappeared.
    for node in EditorInterface.get_selection().get_selected_nodes():
        if node is TargetNodeExample:
            node.callv("example_func") # or with undo/redo...
```

Maybe a similiar approach would work to allow the `@export_tool_button` buttons to activate on all selected nodes of type? (*But using MultiNodeEdit instead*)

Also, currently as a workaround, you could parse the selected nodes yourself in the function that the exported button calls, and then call the actual function you want to call from it.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Create a custom node using `class_name`
2. export a tool button using `@export_tool_button`, calling a function which prints the node name.
3. observe that the function is called only on the node that was selected first.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[mrp-export-tool-button-multinodeedit.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19122905/mrp-export-tool-button-multinodeedit.zip)
